value.value: An anatomical junction between two parts of the digestive tract.

Capillary that has pores in the endothelial cells (60-80 nm in diameter) that are spanned by a diaphragm of radially oriented fibrils and allow small molecules and limited amounts of protein to diffuse.
Portion of the pancreatic duct, external to the pancreas body that connects the pancreas with the hepatopancreatic ampulla.
Structures of the dermis, epidermis, glands and pigment cells recognizable on the external surfaces of the integument.

definition.value: Not clear how this differs from parent class. See https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/issues/1305

value.value: Anatomical projection that is composed of bone or cartilage tissue.
The anatomical junction between the duodenum and the jejunum.

Glandular epithelium of the anal transition zone. The anal transition zone is defined loosely as the tissue interposed between the uninterrupted squamous epithelium of the anoderm and the uninterrupted mucosal epithelium of the anal canal in the anorectum.
A fringe of tissue around the ostium of the fallopian tube, in the direction of the ovary.
A portal vein that drains the descending colon. It is a tributary of the inferior mesenteric vein, and follows the path of its corresponding artery, the left colic artery.
A portal vein that drains the ascending colon. It is a tributary of the superior mesenteric vein, and travels with its corresponding artery, the right colic artery.

The first branch of the inferior mesenteric artery (IMA) is the left colic artery. The left colic artery supplies blood flow to the distal third of the transverse colon and the entirety of the descending colon. Once diverging from the IMA, the left colic artery runs anterior to the left ureter, left internal spermatic vessels (males), and psoas major before branching into its ascending and descending segments.

The right colic artery may arise directly from the superior mesenteric artery (SMA) but often arises from a common trunk with the ileocolic artery or middle colic artery. It supplies the ascending colon.
An anatomical junction between two parts of the intestine.

The trabecular sinus is the lymph-filled space outside the trabeculae between lobules of the lymph node. This is a continuation of the subcapsular sinus which receives the afferent vessels and is present beneath the capsule. This space is traversed by both reticular fibers and cells in the lymph.
A vein where lymph node venules condense and which exits at the lymph node hilum. It is also called hilar vein.
An artery that enters the lymph node at the hilum and branches into smaller arterioles.
An arteriole that arises from the hilar artery of a lymph node and radiates centrifugally, branching in the medulla.

Medullary venules are a continuation of high endothelial venules which condense repeatedly in the interfollicular cortex and peripheral deep cortical unit and then transition to medullary venules at the corticomedullary junction. The medullary venules condense and return centripetally to the hilar vein.

High endothelial venules are specialized blood vessels adapted for lymphocyte trafficking. They form a spatially organized network, which controls both the type of lymphocyte and the site of entry into lymphoid tissues. Uniquely, high endothelial venules express vascular addressins that regulate lymphocyte entry into lymphoid organs. They perform this function in all lymphoid organs except the spleen.

label.value: high endothelial venule of lymph node

value.value: A high endothelial venule that is part of a of lymph node.
A venule that is part of a lymph node.
An arteriole that is part of a lymph node.
A submucosal gland located in a bronchus.

label.value: lymph node germinal center light zone

value.value: Lymph node germinal centers contain two microenvironments: the light zone and the dark zone. The light zone is sparsely populated with B cells and includes additional cell types such as follicular dendritic cells, lymph node tingible macrophages and T follicular helper cells.

label.value: lymph node germinal center dark zone

value.value: Lymph node germinal centers contain two microenvironments: the light zone and the dark zone. The dark zone is densely populated with B cell blasts and reticular cells.
Myenteric nerve plexus that is located in the colon.
Submucous nerve plexus that is located in the colon.
A parasympathetic nerve that releases acetylcholine.

label.value: myenteric nerve plexus of small intestine

value.value: Myenteric nerve plexus that is part of the small intestine.

label.value: submucosal plexus of Meissner submucosal plexus (Meissners plexus, plexus of the submucosa, plexus submucosus)
submucous nerve plexus of small intestine

value.value: Submucous nerve plexus that is located in the small intestine.

The lymph node paracortex is the middle layer of the lymph node and is mostly populated by T cells and dendritic cells. The paracortex also contains specialised blood vessels called high endothelial venules which allow lymphocytes to enter the node.

Follicules in the lymph node are surrounded and separated by the interfollicular cortex. Together with the lymph node follicle, the interfollicular cortex of the lymph node lobule make up the superficial cortex of the lymph node. Capillaries empty into the high endothelial venules located in the interfollicular cortex. The interfollicular cortex also serves as transit corriders for lymphocytes migrating between the B and T cell areas.
The section of the lymph node capsule that faces the subcapsular sinus. In human, it's characterized by specific protein markers.
The section of the lymph node cortex that faces the subcapsular sinus. In human, it's characterized by specific protein markers.
A lymph node sinus intimately associated with paracortical cords that originate in the interfollicular cortex and extend into the medullary cords.
Lymph node paracortical parenchyma containing dense networks of T cells, B cells, fibroblastic reticular cells, and dendritic cells.
A submucosal gland found in a respiratory tract.

Any of the smallest blood vessels where blood circulates within organ tissues. Microvessels include terminal arterioles, metarterioles, capillaries, and venules (but exclude lymphatic capillaries). Arterioles carry oxygenated blood to the capillaries, and blood flows out of the capillaries through venules into veins.
An individual reproductive unit containing a single oocyte and one or several layers of support cells (Armstrong et al., 2020).
An anatomical system that eliminates waste products that arise as a result of metabolic activity.

A lymph node with a lymph center located within the caudal abdomen and pelvis, on the ventral side of the lumbar region. Includes the medial iliac, internal iliac (previously termed hypogastric) and sacral lymph nodes.
A conductive airway that branches into terminal bronchioles.
A muscle tissue that is associated with soft internal organs (viscera).
It is quite common to refer to visceral muscles as smooth muscles, by analogy with vertebrates; however, most visceral muscles in arthropods are actually striated.
A striated muscle tissue that is associated with soft internal organs (viscera).
Branch of conducting airway between a segmental bronchus and a preterminal bronchiole.
Like other bronchi, the walls of a subsegmental bronchus contain plates of cartilage. Notably, the cartilage plates become smaller and more widely dispersed with each branching.

label.value: ciliated ducts of bronchial submucosal gland

value.value: A ciliated duct part of a bronchial submucosal gland.

label.value: terminal ciliated ducts for tracheal submucosal gland

value.value: A ciliated duct part of a tracheal submucosal gland.
A spherical or tubular structure in a submucosal gland that produces and secretes mucus and other substances into the ducts leading to the surface epithelium.
A non-secretory tubular structure in the submucosal gland where secretions are collected before flowing towards the surface epithelium.
